Anthony stuck to her story for three 
years, until her lawyer dropped a bombshell at the  beginning of her 
trial and revealed that the nanny had never existed.

Instead,
she had made up the babysitter using Fernandez-Gonzalez's name. She had the idea after 
she saw her details on an information card when they both visited an apartment 
complex on the same day.

Her
lawyer says after Anthony's claims were made public, Fernandez-Gonzalez
received death threats in the middle of the night against her and her 
children.

She was fired from her job as a housekeeper, and her landlord said he didn't want her on his property.

Fernandez-Gonzalez's
lawyer, John Morgan, told ABC News he plans to interrogate Anthony 
about her daughter's death - a move Anthony's legal team are likely to 
strongly oppose, saying it isn't relevant to the civil case.

Mr Morgan said: 'The first question I'm going to ask her is, "Tell us the last time you 
saw Caylee". The second is, "Tell us when you found out she was dead".'

